  "eprint": {
    "title": "Deterministic-Prover Zero-Knowledge Proofs",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "Hila Dahari",
        "email": "hiladahari41@gmail",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Yehuda Lindell",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "Zero-knowledge proof systems enable a prover to convince a verifier of the\nvalidity of a statement without revealing anything beyond that fact. The role\nof randomness in interactive proofs in general, and in zero-knowledge in\nparticular, is well known. In particular, zero-knowledge with a deterministic\nverifier is  impossible for non-trivial languages (outside of\n$\\mathcal{BPP}$). Likewise, it was shown by Goldreich and Oren (Journal of\nCryptology, 1994) that zero-knowledge with a deterministic prover is also\nimpossible for non-trivial languages. However, their proof holds only for\nauxiliary-input zero knowledge and a malicious verifier.\n\nIn this paper, we initiate the study of the feasibility of zero-knowledge\nproof systems with a deterministic prover in settings not covered by the\nresult of Goldreich and Oren. We prove the existence of deterministic-prover\nauxiliary-input honest-verifier zero-knowledge for any $\\cal NP$\nlanguage, under standard assumptions. In addition, we show that any language\nwith a hash proof system has a deterministic-prover honest-verifier\nstatistical zero-knowledge proof, with an efficient prover. Finally, we show\nthat in some cases, it is even possible to achieve deterministic-prover\nuniform zero-knowledge for a malicious verifier.\nOur contribution is primarily conceptual, and sheds light on the necessity of\nrandomness in zero knowledge in settings where either the verifier is honest\nor there is no auxiliary input.",
    "keywords": [
      "zero knowledge",
      "deterministic prover",
      "foundations",
      "feasibility"
    ],
